The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, April 01, 2004 				 Linc scripts plan for new plant in Bengal
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, March 31: Linc Pen and Plastics Limited has acquired a property to set up its second manufacturing plant in Bengal.																								The new plant should be operational by the end of financial year 2004-05. At present, the company has three units, two in Goa and one in Bengal.																								The company also plans to expand the capacity at its existing plants and take the production level to 10 lakh pens from the current figure of 7 lakh pens a day.																								We intend to finance the total expansion cost of Rs 4-5 crore from our internal accruals, said Deepak Jalan, managing director, Linc Pen and Plastics. 																								This has been a good year for us, said Jalan, while announcing the companys foray into the pencil segment with the launch of Markline range of pencils. We have achieved a growth rate of almost 35 per cent compared with the previous year, whereas the market growth rate is around 10-15 per cent.																								Linc Pen touched last fiscals (2002-03) turnover figure of Rs 62 core within nine months of this fiscal. It expects to close the current year with an estimated turnover of Rs 82 crore. The profit after tax (PAT) for 2002-03 was Rs 2.17 crore, which the company surpassed within nine months of this fiscal with a PAT of Rs 3.3 crore.																								The total market size for pens in India is around Rs 1,000 crore. Of this, the company holds an 8 per cent share and occupies the fifth position following other pen majors such as Cello, Reynolds and Todays.																								Exports constitute 12 per cent of the total revenue of the company with major chunks going to the US and the UK. Jalan said that Linc aims to increase this figure to 25 per cent within the next couple of years.																								The company has a tie-up with international retailing major, Walmart, and is on the lookout for collaborations with other retailing outlets. It also exports, albeit in much smaller quantities, to neighbouring countries like Myanmar and plans to enter Bangladesh once the market there opens up. 
